**No, you do not need `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` on .NET 10.** That property is only for .NET 9 and earlier.

On .NET 10, use the native MTP mode by adding a `test` section to your `global.json`:

```json
{
  "sdk": {
    "version": "10.0.100"
  },
  "test": {
    "runner": "Microsoft.Testing.Platform"
  }
}
```

**Key differences from .NET 9:**

| .NET 9 (old way) | .NET 10 (native) |
|---|---|
| `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in Directory.Build.props | `"test": { "runner": "Microsoft.Testing.Platform" }` in global.json |
| Must use `--` separator: `dotnet test -- --report-trx` | Arguments passed directly: `dotnet test --report-trx` |

You still need the framework-specific runner property (e.g., `EnableMSTestRunner`, `EnableNUnitRunner`, or the appropriate package for xUnit). The `global.json` setting only controls how `dotnet test` communicates with MTP — it doesn't enable MTP in the test project itself.

